Step 1: Set up the Project
Create a New Project in Android Studio.
Select the "Empty Activity" template.
Name your project (e.g., IntentMessageApp) and ensure the language is set to Kotlin. 


Step 2: Design the First Activity Layout (MainActivity)
Open res/layout/activity_main.xml. This layout will contain an EditText for the user to type a message and a Button to send it. 
xml

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<androidx.constraintlayout.widget.ConstraintLayout xmlns:android="schemas.android.com"
    xmlns:app="schemas.android.com"
    xmlns:tools="schemas.android.com"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    tools:context=".MainActivity">

    <EditText
        android:id="@+id/editTextMessage"
        android:layout_width="0dp"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_marginStart="24dp"
        android:layout_marginEnd="24dp"
        android:hint="Enter a message (e.g., Hello)"
        android:minHeight="48dp"
        app:layout_constraintBottom_toTopOf="@+id/buttonSend"
        app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintTop_toTopOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintVertical_chainStyle="packed" />

    <Button
        android:id="@+id/buttonSend"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:layout_marginTop="16dp"
        android:text="Send Message"
        app:layout_constraintBottom_toBottomOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintTop_toBottomOf="@+id/editTextMessage" />

</androidx.constraintlayout.widget.ConstraintLayout>


Step 3: Implement the First Activity Logic (MainActivity.kt) 
Open app/src/main/java/.../MainActivity.kt. In this file, we set up an onClickListener for the button to capture the message, create an Intent, add the message as an "extra" to the Intent, and start the SecondActivity. 
kotlin
package com.yourdomain.intentmessageapp // Replace with your package name

import android.content.Intent
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity
import android.os.Bundle
import android.widget.Button
import android.widget.EditText

class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {

    companion object {
        // Define a key for the Intent extra
        const val EXTRA_MESSAGE = "com.yourdomain.intentmessageapp.MESSAGE"
    }

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main)

        val messageEditText = findViewById<EditText>(R.id.editTextMessage)
        val sendButton = findViewById<Button>(R.id.buttonSend)

        sendButton.setOnClickListener {
            val message = messageEditText.text.toString()

            // Create an Intent to start SecondActivity
            val intent = Intent(this, SecondActivity::class.java).apply {
                // Put the message as an "extra" into the Intent
                putExtra(EXTRA_MESSAGE, message)
            }
            // Start the new activity
            startActivity(intent)
        }
    }
}


Step 4: Create the Second Activity 
You need a new activity to receive and display the message. 
Right-click on your package name in the app/src/main/java folder.
Select New > Activity > Empty Activity.
Name it SecondActivity. 


Step 5: Design the Second Activity Layout (SecondActivity) 
Open res/layout/activity_second.xml. This layout will just have a TextView to display the received message. 
xml


<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<androidx.constraintlayout.widget.ConstraintLayout xmlns:android="schemas.android.com"
    xmlns:app="schemas.android.com"
    xmlns:tools="http-go.google.com"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    tools:context=".SecondActivity">

    <TextView
        android:id="@+id/textViewReceivedMessage"
        android:layout_width="wrap_content"
        android:layout_height="wrap_content"
        android:text="Message goes here"
        android:textSize="24sp"
        android:textStyle="bold"
        app:layout_constraintBottom_toBottomOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintEnd_toEndOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintStart_toStartOf="parent"
        app:layout_constraintTop_toTopOf="parent" />

</androidx.constraintlayout.widget.ConstraintLayout>


Step 6: Implement the Second Activity Logic (SecondActivity.kt)
Open app/src/main/java/.../SecondActivity.kt. Here, we retrieve the Intent that started this activity, extract the message extra using the same key defined in MainActivity, and display it in the TextView. 
kotlin


package com.yourdomain.intentmessageapp // Replace with your package name

import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity
import android.os.Bundle
import android.widget.TextView

class SecondActivity : AppCompatActivity() {
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_second)

        // Get the Intent that started this activity and extract the string
        val message = intent.getStringExtra(MainActivity.EXTRA_MESSAGE)

        // Capture the layout's TextView and set the string as its text
        val textView = findViewById<TextView>(R.id.textViewReceivedMessage).apply {
            text = message
        }
    }
}


Step 7: Run the Application
Build and run your application on an emulator or a physical device. 
On the first screen, type your "Hello" message into the text field.
Tap the "Send Message" button.
The second activity will open, displaying the message you entered. 